<item>
            <title>[CASSANDRA-11216] Range.compareTo() violates the contract of Comparable</title>
                <link>https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/CASSANDRA-11216</link>
                <project id="12310865" key="CASSANDRA">Apache Cassandra</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;When running some quick-check style tests, I discovered that if both of the ranges being compared wrap around, then the result of the comparison depends on which range is evaluated first. For example, two ranges:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A = &lt;/p&gt;
{ -1, 2 }
&lt;p&gt;B = &lt;/p&gt;
{ -2, 1 }

&lt;p&gt;and then compare them together:&lt;br/&gt;
A.compareTo(B) == -1&lt;br/&gt;
B.compareTo(A) == -1&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This is because the logic of the existing &lt;tt&gt;Range.compareTo()&lt;/tt&gt; simply checks to see if the &lt;tt&gt;this&lt;/tt&gt; range wraps around, and returns -1. This bug does not appear to affect c* until 3.0, and then only in one place (&lt;tt&gt;MerkleTrees.TokenRangeComparator#compare&lt;/tt&gt;) that I could identify.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
